President Biden has declared a major disaster in the state of Minnesota due to severe storms, straight-line winds, and flooding that occurred between April 22 and June 15, 2022. This declaration allows for federal assistance to supplement state, tribal, and local recovery efforts in the affected areas. Federal funding will be provided on a cost-sharing basis for emergency work, as well as the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The designated counties include Beltrami, Clearwater, Cook, Kittson, Koochiching, Lake, Lake of the Woods, Mahnomen, Marshall, Norman, Pennington, Polk, Red Lake, Roseau, and St. Louis, as well as the Bois Forte Band of Chippewa, Leech Lake Band of Ojibwe, Red Lake Nation, and the White Earth Nation. Hazard mitigation measures in all areas within the state are also eligible for federal funding. Brian F. Schiller has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations, and additional designations may be made in the future if requested by the state and warranted by further damage assessments. For more information, media can contact the FEMA News Desk at (202) 646-3272 or FEMA-NEWS-DESK@FEMA.DHS.GOV.